    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"spookiness\" of entanglement can be attributed to the fact that, when two particles are entangled, their wave functions become \"entangled\" in a way that can't be reduced to a classical description. Mathematically, this is represented by the use of entangled states, such as the Bell state. When you measure one particle, the state of the other particle is instantly affected, regardless of the distance between them. This is because the wave function of the entangled system is a superposition of multiple classical states, and when you measure one particle, the superposition \"collapses\" to a specific state, affecting the other particle instantaneously. This effect is a direct result of the mathematical structure of quantum mechanics, specifically the use of Hilbert spaces and linear operators.",
